Ok my bad, registry wasn't started properly due to S3 `boto.exception.S3ResponseError: S3ResponseError: 403 Forbidden`.
Strange my policy looked like:
```
{
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Action": "s3:*",
            "Resource": [
                "arn:aws:s3:::deis-bucket/*",
                "arn:aws:s3:::deis-bucket"
            ]
        }
    ]
}
```

I was thinking that would be enough but had to add `"arn:aws:s3:::*"` in resources and now it works fine.
I would like to not permit the user to access to all buckets. Do you have some advice ?

I wait Deis to be correctly installed before close the issue.

@gsalgado I have tinkered a bit with the idea of creating the PeerPool and passing in a `Future[DiscoveryProtocol]` (aka `Awaitable[DiscoveryProtocol]`). It's not pretty yet because it basically just pushes down the problem one level deeper (now `PeerPool` will magically have the `self.discovery` appearing in the *done callback*)

But it's really just earlier WIP stuff anyway and it's my first attempt of getting my feet wet with asyncio in Python :sweat_smile: 

https://github.com/ethereum/py-evm/pull/886

Let me copy over your comment from https://github.com/ethereum/py-evm/issues/592#issuecomment-386040975

>Also worth pointing out that this is the reason for the `Configurable` API.

>Instead of having to define all of these classes just for testing you can do this.

```python
@pytest.fixture(params=[FrontierVM, HomesteadVM, ...])
def chain_for_testing(request):
    return Chain.configure(vm_configuration=((0, request.param),))
```

I have a couple of thoughts on that but I think I'll let them mature for a while and maybe come back with a bit of code at some point to discuss further. It's not something that *needs* to be addressed but rather just worth exploring if it can be improved. Thanks for leaving your thoughts and providing the background information about why we use that pattern!

