If you are installing on bash, you should install on WSL (Windows Subsystem Linux).  `git bash` is not the same and not supported. It will generally work, but you will very likely run into problems using it.

For Windows you can install using an MSI.  https://aka.ms/InstallAzureCliWindows

@derekbekoe we should probably update the install instructions on the landing page to reference the different ways on installing. I had to search for Azure CLI MSI to find this link.

@troydai the extension likely fails because of a missing dependency. 
If the extension fails to bring in the right packages, it is not the fault of the CLI, and the script won't fail because of it. 
The script WILL fail once a change in the CLI causes extension commands that were properly working to throw errors.

