One possible alternative to prevent typos from passing silently would be to pass a set of allowed metadata keys.

```python
class BaseSchema(Schema):
    class Meta:
        allowed_field_metadata = {
            'description',
         }
```

An error would be raised if metadata outside of that set were passed.

> Pickled objects will probably not be stored in the long term, just the time of sending a message to the next and we can reasonably expect that all the Python processes communicating together in such a system will have the same version so using `HIGHEST_PROTOCOL` should be fine in that context.

Totally in agreement with this. I think we should switch to `HIGHEST_PROTOCOL` by default. For the users I support, their primary use is on Spark. I'd prefer the performance over potential Python process interop. As long as the drivers and the executors match, I think we're ok.

@rdblue -- when people run our Python3 kernel with Spark, does the executor match the driver?

True, it's not needed for that particular example, even though in a sense we'd be executing two transactions (one running the constructor, followed by the transaction executing the runtime bytecode).

I think in more complex cases, "finding any writes to param" in a reliable way will become challenging, because there might be cases where multiple intermediate steps are necessary for the write to become possible. Maybe something like this:


```
contract Wut {
    uint256 private param;

    function Wut() public {
        param = 0;
    }
    function inc() {
        param += 1;
    }
    function run() {
        assert(param > 3);
    }
}
```

